  "prompt": "Why do I feel sleepy and tired after consuming non-drowsy cold/flu-relief medication?",
  "response": "Feeling sleepy or tired after taking non-drowsy cold or flu relief medication can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. **Inactive Ingredients**: Some non-drowsy formulations may still contain ingredients that can cause sedation in certain individuals. For example, some medications may contain small amounts of antihistamines, which can lead to drowsiness.\n\n2. **Individual Response**: Everyone metabolizes medications differently, and some individuals may be more sensitive to the active ingredients, causing fatigue despite the intended non-drowsy effect.\n\n3. **Underlying Illness**: If you're taking cold or flu-relief medication, your body is likely already engaged in fighting off an infection. This can lead to fatigue, regardless of the medications you're taking.\n\n4. **Dehydration**: Cold and flu symptoms may cause a decrease in fluid intake, and some medications can have dehydrating effects, leading to fatigue.\n\n5. **Other Ingredients**: Some formulations contain ingredients like acetaminophen or ibuprofen that can cause drowsiness in some people, especially if taken at higher doses.\n\n6. **Sleep Disruption**: You may also have disrupted sleep due to your illness, which can lead to feelings of tiredness even when taking medication designed to keep you alert.\n\n7. **Interaction with Other Medications**: If you're taking other medications or supplements, there may be interactions that cause increased drowsiness or fatigue.\n\nIf you are consistently experiencing excessive drowsiness after taking these medications, it's a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional to explore other options or check for underlying health issues.",
